# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: avif-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:avif-format/av1] Like VP9, but unlike H.264 (AVC) and H.265 (HEVC), AV1 has a royalty-free licensing model that does not hinder adoption in open-source projects.
[src:avif-format/av1] AVIF is an image file format that uses AV1 compression algorithms.
[src:avif-format/av1] The Alliance's motivations for creating AV1 included the high cost and uncertainty involved with the patent licensing of HEVC (also known as H.265), the MPEG-designed codec expected to succeed AVC.
[src:avif-format/av1] Additionally, the Alliance's seven founding members – Amazon, Cisco, Google, Intel, Microsoft, Mozilla, and Netflix – announced that the initial focus of the video format would be delivery of high-quality web video.
[src:avif-format/av1] The official announcement of AV1 came with the press release on the formation of the Alliance for Open Media on 1 September 2015.
[src:avif-format/av1] Only 42 days before, on 21 July 2015, HEVC Advance's initial licensing offer was announced to be an increase over the royalty fees of its predecessor, AVC.
[src:avif-format/av1] In addition to the increased cost, the complexity of the licensing process increased with HEVC.
[src:avif-format/av1] Unlike previous MPEG standards where the technology in the standard could be licensed from a single entity, MPEG LA, when the HEVC standard was finished, two patent pools had been formed with a third pool on the horizon.
[src:avif-format/av1] In addition, various patent holders were refusing to license patents via either pool, increasing uncertainty about HEVC's licensing.
[src:avif-format/av1] According to Microsoft's Ian LeGrow, an open-source, royalty-free technology was seen as the easiest way to eliminate this uncertainty around licensing.
[src:avif-format/av1] The negative effect of patent licensing on free and open-source software has also been cited as a reason for the creation of AV1.
[src:avif-format/av1] For example, building an H.264 implementation into Firefox would prevent it from being distributed free of charge since licensing fees would have to be paid to MPEG-LA.
[src:avif-format/av1] Free Software Foundation Europe has argued that FRAND patent licensing practices make the free software implementation of standards impossible due to various incompatibilities with free-software licenses.
[src:avif-format/av1] Many of the components of the AV1 project were sourced from previous research efforts by Alliance members.
[src:avif-format/av1] Individual contributors had started experimental technology platforms years before: Xiph's/Mozilla's Daala published code in 2010, Google's experimental VP9 evolution project VP10 was announced on 12 September 2014, and Cisco's Thor was published on 11 August 2015.
[src:avif-format/av1] Building on the code base of VP9, AV1 incorporates additional techniques, several of which were developed in these experimental formats.
[src:avif-format/av1] Many companies are part of Alliance for Open Media, including Samsung, Vimeo, Microsoft, Netflix, Mozilla, AMD, Nvidia, Intel, ARM, Google, Facebook, Cisco, Amazon, Hulu, VideoLAN, Adobe, and Apple.
[src:avif-format/av1] Apple is an AOMedia governing member, although it joined after the formation.
[src:avif-format/av1] The management of the AV1 streams has been officially included among the typological videos manageable by Coremedia.
[src:avif-format/av1] The first version 0.1.0 of the AV1 reference codec was published on April 7, 2016.
[src:avif-format/av1] Although a soft feature freeze came into effect at the end of October 2017, development continued on several significant features.
[src:avif-format/av1] The bitstream format, was projected to be frozen in January 2018 but was delayed due to unresolved critical bugs as well as further changes to transformations, syntax, the prediction of motion vectors, and the completion of legal analysis.
[src:avif-format/av1] The Alliance announced the release of the AV1 bitstream specification on March 28, 2018, along with a reference, software-based encoder and decoder.
[src:avif-format/av1] On 25 June 2018, a validated version 1.0.0 of the specification was released.
[src:avif-format/av1] On January 8, 2019, a validated *version 1.0.0 with Errata 1* of the specification was released.
[src:avif-format/av1] Martin Smole from AOM member Bitmovin said that the computational efficiency was the greatest remaining challenge after the bitstream format freeze had been completed.
[src:avif-format/av1] While working on the format, the encoder was not targeted for production use and speed optimizations were not prioritized.
[src:avif-format/av1] Consequently, the early version of AV1 was orders of magnitude slower than existing HEVC encoders.
[src:avif-format/av1] Much of the development effort was consequently shifted towards improving the reference encoder.
[src:avif-format/av1] In March 2019, it was reported that the speed of the reference encoder had improved greatly and was within the same order of magnitude as encoders for other common formats.
[src:avif-format/av1] On January 21, 2021, the MIME type of AV1 was defined as `video/AV1`.
[src:avif-format/av1] The usage of AV1 using this MIME type is restricted to Real-time Transport Protocol purposes only.
[src:avif-format/av1] For AOM's 10th birthday, the Alliance announced the successor to AV1 called AV2.
[src:avif-format/av1] It is designed to deliver better compression performance, enhanced support for AR, VR and split-screen usage and support for a wider visual quality range.
[src:avif-format/av1] AV1 aims to be a video format for the web that is both state-of-the-art and royalty free.
[src:avif-format/av1] This concern has been raised regarding AV1, and previously VP8, VP9, Theora and IVC.
[src:avif-format/av1] The problem is not unique to royalty-free formats, but it uniquely threatens their *status* as royalty-free.
[src:avif-format/av1] To fulfill the goal of being royalty free, the development process requires that no feature can be adopted before it has been confirmed independently by two separate parties to not infringe on patents of competing companies.
[src:avif-format/av1] In cases where an alternative to a patent-protected technique is not available, owners of relevant patents have been invited to join the Alliance (even if they were already members of another patent pool).
[src:avif-format/av1] For example, Alliance members Apple, Cisco, Google, and Microsoft are also licensors in MPEG-LA's patent pool for H.264.
[src:avif-format/av1] As an additional protection for the royalty-free status of AV1, the Alliance has a legal defense fund to aid smaller Alliance members or AV1 licensees in the event they are sued for alleged patent infringement.
[src:avif-format/av1] Under patent rules adopted from the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), technology contributors license their AV1-connected patents to anyone, anywhere, anytime based on reciprocity (i.e. as long as the user does not engage in patent litigation).
[src:avif-format/av1] As a defensive condition, anyone engaging in patent litigation loses the right to the patents of *all* patent holders.
[src:avif-format/av1] This treatment of intellectual property rights (IPR), and its absolute priority during development, is contrary to extant MPEG formats like AVC and HEVC.
[src:avif-format/av1] These were developed under an IPR uninvolvement policy by their standardization organisations, as stipulated in the ITU-T's definition of an open standard.
[src:avif-format/av1] However, MPEG's chairman has argued this practice has to change, which it is: EVC is also set to have a royalty-free subset, and will have switchable features in its bitstream to defend against future IPR threats.
[src:avif-format/av1] The creation of royalty-free web standards has been a long-stated pursuit for the industry.
[src:avif-format/av1] In 2007, the proposal for HTML video specified Theora as mandatory to implement.
[src:avif-format/av1] The reason was that public content should be encoded in freely implementable formats, if only as a "baseline format", and that changing such a baseline format later would be hard because of network effects.
[src:avif-format/av1] The Alliance for Open Media is a continuation of Google's efforts with the WebM project, which renewed the royalty-free competition after Theora had been surpassed by AVC.
[src:avif-format/av1] For companies such as Mozilla that distribute free software, AVC can be difficult to support as a per-copy royalty is unsustainable given the lack of revenue stream to support these payments in free software (see FRAND § Excluding costless distribution).
[src:avif-format/av1] Similarly, HEVC has not successfully convinced all licensors to allow an exception for freely distributed software (see HEVC § Provision for costless software).
[src:avif-format/av1] The performance goals include "a step up from VP9 and HEVC" in efficiency for a low increase in complexity.
[src:avif-format/av1] NETVC's efficiency goal is 25% improvement over HEVC.
[src:avif-format/av1] The primary complexity concern is for software decoding, since hardware support will take time to reach users.
[src:avif-format/av1] However, for WebRTC, live encoding performance is also relevant, which is Cisco's agenda: Cisco is a manufacturer of videoconferencing equipment, and their Thor contributions aim at "reasonable compression at only moderate complexity".
[src:avif-format/av1] It is therefore planned to support the color space from ITU-R Recommendation BT.2020 and up to 12 bits of precision per color component.
[src:avif-format/av1] AV1 is primarily intended for lossy encoding, although lossless compression is supported as well.
[src:avif-format/av1] AV1 is a traditional block-based frequency transform format featuring new techniques.
[src:avif-format/av1] Based on Google's VP9, AV1 incorporates additional techniques that mainly give encoders more coding options to enable better adaptation to different types of input.
[src:avif-format/av1] The Alliance published a reference implementation written in C and assembly language (`aomenc`, `aomdec`) as free software under the terms of the BSD 2-Clause License.
[src:avif-format/av1] Development happens in public and is open for contributions, regardless of AOM membership.
[src:avif-format/av1] When the feature gained some support in the community, the experiment was enabled by default, and ultimately had its flag removed when all of the reviews were passed.
[src:avif-format/av1] Experiment names were lowercased in the *configure* script and uppercased in conditional compilation flags.
[src:avif-format/av1] To better and more reliably support HDR and color spaces, corresponding metadata can now be integrated into the video bitstream instead of being signaled in the container.
[src:avif-format/av1] Frame content is separated into adjacent same-sized blocks referred to as superblocks.
[src:avif-format/av1] Similar to the concept of a macroblock, superblocks are square-shaped and can either be of size 128×128 or 64×64 pixels.
[src:avif-format/av1] Superblocks can be divided in smaller blocks according to different partitioning patterns.
[src:avif-format/av1] The four-way split pattern is the only pattern whose partitions can be recursively subdivided.
[src:avif-format/av1] This allows superblocks to be divided into partitions as small as 4×4 pixels.
[src:avif-format/av1] "T-shaped" partitioning patterns are introduced, a feature developed for VP10, as well as horizontal or vertical splits into four stripes of 4:1 and 1:4 aspect ratio.
[src:avif-format/av1] The available partitioning patterns vary according to the block size, both 128×128 and 8×8 blocks can't use 4:1 and 1:4 splits.
[src:avif-format/av1] Moreover, 8×8 blocks can't use T-shaped splits.
[src:avif-format/av1] Two separate predictions can now be used on spatially different parts of a block using a smooth, oblique transition line (*wedge-partitioned prediction*).
[src:avif-format/av1] This enables more accurate separation of objects without the traditional staircase lines along the boundaries of square blocks.
[src:avif-format/av1] More encoder parallelism is possible thanks to configurable prediction dependency between tile rows (`ext_tile`).
[src:avif-format/av1] AV1 performs internal processing in higher precision (10 or 12 bits per sample), which leads to quality improvement by reducing rounding errors.
[src:avif-format/av1] This allows the combination of either two inter predictions or an inter and an intra prediction to be used in the same block.
[src:avif-format/av1] A frame can reference 6 instead of 3 of the 8 available frame buffers for temporal (inter) prediction while providing more flexibility on bi-prediction (`ext_refs`).
[src:avif-format/av1] The *Warped Motion* (`warped_motion`) and *Global Motion* (`global_motion`) tools in AV1 aim to reduce redundant information in motion vectors by recognizing patterns arising from camera motion.
[src:avif-format/av1] They implement ideas that were attempted in preceding formats like e.g.
[src:avif-format/av1] MPEG-4 ASP, albeit with a novel approach that works in three dimensions.
[src:avif-format/av1] There can be a set of warping parameters for a whole frame offered in the bitstream, or blocks can use a set of implicit local parameters that get computed based on surrounding blocks.
[src:avif-format/av1] Intra prediction consists of predicting the pixels of given blocks only using information available in the current frame.
[src:avif-format/av1] Most often, intra predictions are built from the neighboring pixels above and to the left of the predicted block.
[src:avif-format/av1] The DC predictor builds a prediction by averaging the pixels above and to the left of block.
[src:avif-format/av1] Directional predictors extrapolate these neighboring pixels according to a specified angle.
[src:avif-format/av1] In AV1, 8 main directional modes can be chosen.
[src:avif-format/av1] These modes start at an angle of 45 degrees and increase by a step size of 22.5 degrees up until 203 degrees.
[src:avif-format/av1] Furthermore, for each directional mode, six offsets of 3 degrees can be signaled for bigger blocks, three above the main angle and three below it, resulting in a total of 56 angles (`ext_intra`).
[src:avif-format/av1] The "TrueMotion" predictor was replaced with a Paeth predictor which looks at the difference from the known pixel in the above-left corner to the pixel directly above and directly left of the new one and then chooses the one that lies in direction of the smaller gradient as predictor.
[src:avif-format/av1] A palette predictor is available for blocks with up to 8 dominant colors, such as some computer screen content.
[src:avif-format/av1] Correlations between the luminosity and the color information can now be exploited with a predictor for chroma blocks that is based on samples from the luma plane (`cfl`), a technique borrowed from Daala.
[src:avif-format/av1] In order to reduce visible boundaries along borders of inter-predicted blocks, a technique called overlapped block motion compensation (OBMC) can be used.
[src:avif-format/av1] This involves extending a block's size so that it overlaps with neighboring blocks by 2 to 32 pixels, and blending the overlapping parts together.
[src:avif-format/av1] It can combine two one-dimensional transforms in order to use different transforms for the horizontal and the vertical dimension (`ext_tx`).
[src:avif-format/av1] AV1 has new optimized quantization matrices (`aom_qm`).
[src:avif-format/av1] The eight sets of quantization parameters that can be selected and signaled for each frame now have individual parameters for the two chroma planes and can use spatial prediction.
[src:avif-format/av1] On every new superblock, the quantization parameters can be adjusted by signaling an offset.
[src:avif-format/av1] In-loop filtering combines Thor's constrained low-pass filter and Daala's directional deringing filter into the *Constrained Directional Enhancement Filter*, `cdef`.
[src:avif-format/av1] This is an edge-directed conditional replacement filter that smooths blocks roughly along the direction of the dominant edge to eliminate ringing artifacts.
[src:avif-format/av1] There is also the *loop restoration filter* (`loop_restoration`) based on the Wiener filter and self-guided restoration filters to remove blur artifacts due to block processing.
[src:avif-format/av1] Daala's entropy coder (`daala_ec`), a non-binary arithmetic coder, was selected for replacing VP9's binary entropy coder.
[src:avif-format/av1] The use of *non-binary* arithmetic coding helps evade patents but also adds bit-level parallelism to an otherwise serial process, reducing clock rate demands on hardware implementations.
[src:avif-format/av1] This is to say that the effectiveness of modern binary arithmetic coding like CABAC is being approached using a greater alphabet than binary, hence greater speed, as in Huffman code (but not as simple and fast as Huffman code).
[src:avif-format/av1] AV1 also gained the ability to adapt the symbol probabilities in the arithmetic coder per coded symbol instead of per frame (`ec_adapt`).
[src:avif-format/av1] AV1 has provisions for temporal and spatial scalability.
[src:avif-format/av1] A first comparison from the beginning of June 2016 found AV1 roughly on par with HEVC, as did one using code from late January 2017.
[src:avif-format/av1] In April 2017, using the 8 enabled experimental features at the time (of 77 total), Bitmovin was able to demonstrate favorable objective metrics, as well as visual results, compared to HEVC on the *Sintel* and *Tears of Steel* short films.
[src:avif-format/av1] A follow-up comparison by Jan Ozer of *Streaming Media Magazine* confirmed this, and concluded that "AV1 is at least as good as HEVC now".
[src:avif-format/av1] Ozer noted that his and Bitmovin's results contradicted a comparison by Fraunhofer Institute for Telecommunications from late 2016 that had found AV1 65.7% less efficient than HEVC, underperforming even H.264/AVC which they concluded as being 10.5% more efficient.
[src:avif-format/av1] Ozer justified this discrepancy by having used encoding parameters endorsed by each encoder vendor, as well as having more features in the newer AV1 encoder.
[src:avif-format/av1] Decoding performance was at about half the speed of VP9 according to internal measurements from 2017.
[src:avif-format/av1] Tests from Netflix in 2017, based on measurements with PSNR and VMAF at 720p, showed that AV1 was about 25% more efficient than VP9 (libvpx).
[src:avif-format/av1] Tests from Facebook conducted in 2018, based on PSNR, showed that the AV1 reference encoder was able to achieve 34%, 46.2% and 50.3% higher data compression than libvpx-vp9, x264 High profile, and x264 Main profile respectively.
[src:avif-format/av1] Tests from Moscow State University in 2017 found that VP9 required 31% and HEVC 22% more bitrate than AV1 in order to achieve similar levels of quality.
[src:avif-format/av1] The AV1 encoder was operating at speed "2500–3500 times lower than competitors" due to the lack of optimization (which was not available at that time).
[src:avif-format/av1] Tests from University of Waterloo in 2020 found that when using a mean opinion score (MOS) for 2160p (4K) video AV1 had the bitrate saving of 9.5% compared to HEVC and 16.4% compared to VP9.
[src:avif-format/av1] They also concluded that at the time of the study at 2160p the AV1 video encodes on average took 590× longer compared to encoding with AVC; while HEVC took on average 4.2× longer and VP9 took on average 5.2× longer than AVC respectively.
[src:avif-format/av1] The best-in-test AV1 encoder, Visionular's Aurora1, in its "slower" preset, was as fast as *x265 veryslow* while saving 50% bitrate over *x264 veryslow*.
[src:avif-format/av1] CapFrameX tested the GPUs performance with AV1 decoding.
[src:avif-format/av1] On 5 October 2022, Cloudflare announced that it has a beta player.
[src:avif-format/av1] AV1 defines three profiles for decoders which are Main, High, and Professional.
[src:avif-format/av1] The Main profile allows for a bit depth of 8 or 10 bits per sample with 4:0:0 (greyscale) and 4:2:0 (quarter) chroma sampling.
[src:avif-format/av1] The High profile further adds support for 4:4:4 chroma sampling (no subsampling).
[src:avif-format/av1] The Professional profile extends capabilities to full support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2 (half) and 4:4:4 chroma sub-sampling with 8, 10 and 12 bit color depths.
[src:avif-format/av1] AV1 defines levels for decoders with maximum variables for levels ranging from 2.0 to 6.3.
[src:avif-format/av1] The levels that can be implemented depend on the hardware capability.
[src:avif-format/av1] A "Level 7" is mentioned but is not defined.
[src:avif-format/av1] AV1 video is usually accompanied with AAC or Opus audio in an ISO base media file format (MP4) container.
[src:avif-format/av1] In October 2016, Netflix stated they expected to be an early adopter of AV1.
[src:avif-format/av1] On 5 February 2020, Netflix began using AV1 to stream select titles on Android, providing 20% improved compression efficiency over their VP9 streams.
[src:avif-format/av1] On 9 November 2021, Netflix announced it had begun streaming AV1 content to a number of TVs with AV1 decoders as well as the PlayStation 4 Pro.
[src:avif-format/av1] In December 2025 they reported that 30% of their streams use AV1.
[src:avif-format/av1] In 2018, YouTube began deploying AV1, starting with its AV1 Beta Launch Playlist.
[src:avif-format/av1] According to the description, the videos are (to begin with) encoded at high bitrate to test decoding performance, and YouTube has "ambitious goals" for rolling out AV1.
[src:avif-format/av1] YouTube for Android TV supports playback of videos encoded in AV1 on capable platforms as of version 2.10.13, released in early 2020.
[src:avif-format/av1] In 2020, YouTube started serving videos at 8K resolution in AV1.
[src:avif-format/av1] In February 2019, Facebook followed its own positive test results, by saying it would gradually roll out the AV1 codec as soon as browser support emerges, starting with its most popular videos.
[src:avif-format/av1] MSVP (Meta Scalable Video Processor) was announced and the symposis was published in a popular scientific research website on 15 October 2022.
[src:avif-format/av1] On 4 November 2022, the AV1 codec was announced with the article of Meta technology blog and with Mark Zuckerberg on Instagram Reels which shows AV1 codec compared with H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:avif-format/av1] Citing "Our Instagram engineering team developed a way to dramatically improve video quality.
[src:avif-format/av1] We made basic video processing 94% faster." Android has preliminary native AV1 playback.
[src:avif-format/av1] In June 2019, Vimeo's videos in the "Staff picks" channel were available in AV1 and Opus.
[src:avif-format/av1] Vimeo is using and contributing to Mozilla's Rav1e encoder and expects, with further encoder improvements, to eventually provide AV1 support for all videos uploaded to Vimeo as well as the company's "Live" offering.
[src:avif-format/av1] On 30 April 2020, iQIYI announced support for AV1 for users on PC web browsers and Android devices, according to the announcement, as the first Chinese video streaming site to adopt the codec.
[src:avif-format/av1] Twitch deployed AV1 for its most popular content in 2022 or 2023, with universal support projected to arrive in 2024 or 2025.
[src:avif-format/av1] In April 2021, Roku removed the YouTube TV app from the Roku streaming platform after a contract expired.
[src:avif-format/av1] It was later reported that Roku streaming devices do not use processors that support the AV1 codec.
[src:avif-format/av1] In December 2021, YouTube and Roku agreed to a multiyear deal to keep both the YouTube TV app and the YouTube app on the Roku streaming platform.
[src:avif-format/av1] Roku had argued that using processors in their streaming devices that support the royalty-free AV1 codec would increase costs to consumers.
[src:avif-format/av1] In January 2022, Bilibili rolled out H.265 HEVC and AV1 encoding to videos with high view-count, while videos with lower view-count are only available in H.264 AVC.
[src:avif-format/av1] In July 2024, DMM.com deployed AV1 on its DMM.TV service, becoming the first Japanese company to do so.
[src:avif-format/av1] Other vendors had announced encoders, including EVE for AV1, NGCodec, Socionext, Aurora and MilliCast.
[src:avif-format/av1] There are several hardware accelerators for AV1, typically as part of a GPU or system on a chip.
[src:avif-format/av1] For example, later-generation NVidia GPUs have dedicated hardware and the NVENC and NVDEC APIs for encoding and decoding AV1 and other codecs.
[src:avif-format/av1] In early 2019, Sisvel, a Luxembourg-based company, claimed to be forming a patent pool of patents essential to AV1.
[src:avif-format/av1] This development has not caused Google to reevaluate its planned AV1 usage and the Alliance for Open Media has stated they remain confident that AV1 still overcomes the environment of "high patent royalty requirements and licensing uncertainty".
[src:avif-format/av1] Sisvel began selling licenses to the pool, which contains patents from Philips, GE, NTT, Ericsson, Dolby, and Toshiba in 2020.
[src:avif-format/av1] Unified Patents has been tracking challenges to various patents in the pool.
[src:avif-format/av1] On 7 July 2022, it was revealed that the European Union's antitrust regulators had opened an investigation into AOM and its licensing policy.
[src:avif-format/av1] It said this action may be restricting the innovators' ability to compete with the AV1 technical specification, and may eliminate incentives for them to innovate.
[src:avif-format/av1] On 23 May 2023, the European Commission decided to close the investigation while taking no further action.
[src:avif-format/av1] But in an email they reiterated that the closure does not constitute a finding of compliance or non-compliance with EU antitrust laws.
[src:avif-format/av1] In October 2023, patent pool operator Avanci announced the start of a new licensing program targeting video streaming operators that use AV1 in addition to H.265, H.266, VP9, etc.
[src:avif-format/av1] In March 2026, Dolby sued Snapchat for Video patent infringement in the United States District Court for the District of Delaware (D.
[src:avif-format/av1] Snap Inc.)) and in the Rio de Janeiro State Court in Brazil (Case no.
[src:avif-format/av1] In May 2026, the 5th Business Court of Rio de Janeiro granted Dolby IP Bridge preliminary injunction against Skyworth.
[src:avif-format/av1] The judge baned implementation of patented technologies in current and upcomming products sold in Brazil.
[src:avif-format/av1] Also in the same month Malikie Innovations sued TCL Technology over AV1 patents in United States District Court for the Eastern District of Texas.
[src:avif-format/av1] AV1 Image File Format (AVIF) is an image file format specification for storing still images or image sequences compressed with AV1 in the HEIF file format.
[src:avif-format/av1] It competes with HEIC which uses the same container format, built upon ISOBMFF, but HEVC for compression.
[src:avif-format/avif] An AVIF file is designed to be a conformant HEIF file for both image items and image sequences.
[src:avif-format/avif] Specifically, this specification follows the recommendations given in "Annex I: Guidelines On Defining New Image Formats and Brands" of HEIF.
[src:avif-format/avif] This specification reuses syntax and semantics used in the specification for the AV1 Codec ISO Media File Format Binding.
[src:avif-format/avif] In tests by Netflix in 2020, AVIF showed better compression efficiency than JPEG, as well as better detail preservation, fewer blocking artifacts and less color bleeding around hard edges in composites of natural images, text, and graphics.
[src:avif-format/avif] AVIF has been supported by all major web browsers since 2024, with over 93% of users worldwide on compatible browsers.
[src:avif-format/avif] On 14 December 2018, Netflix published the first .avif sample images.
[src:avif-format/avif] In November 2020, HDR sample images with PQ transfer function and BT.2020 color primaries were published.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] HEIF can store images encoded with multiple coding formats, for example both SDR and HDR images.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] HEVC is an image and video encoding format and the default image codec used with HEIF.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] HEIF files containing HEVC-encoded images are also known as **HEIC** files and are mandated to use the `.heic` filename extension or `.heics` as stated in the standard.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Such files require less storage space than the equivalent-quality JPEG files of the same images.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] HEIF files are a special case of the ISO base media file format (ISOBMFF, ISO/IEC 14496-12), first defined in 2001 as a shared part of MP4 and JPEG 2000.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Introduced in 2015, it was developed by the Moving Picture Experts Group (MPEG) and is defined as Part 12 within the MPEG-H media suite (ISO/IEC 23008-12).
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The requirements and main use cases of HEIF were defined in 2013.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The technical development of the specification took about one and a half years and was finalized in the middle of 2015.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Apple was the first major adopter of the format in 2017 with the introduction of iOS 11 using the HEIC variant.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] While HEIC became the default for iPhones, it is possible to revert the settings to allow photos to be recorded in the JPEG format.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Android devices containing the appropriate hardware encoders received support for HEIC files with the release of Android 10 (2019).
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Although HEIC is gaining in popularity, it is not universally supported; Adobe Photoshop is an example of common image-editing software that only supports HEIC with color depth of 8-bit, and not 10- or 12-bit.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] As of 2022 camera hardware (including on mobile devices) is increasingly supporting HEIC file output, with color depth often higher than 8-bit color.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Storage of individual images, image properties and thumbnails.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] by the rendering software using editing instructions stored separately in the HEIF file.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] These instructions (rectangular cropping, rotation by one, two or three quarter-turns, timed graphic overlays, etc.) and images are stored separately in the HEIF file, and describe specific transformations to be applied to the input images.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The storage overhead of derived images is small.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] animation), their properties and thumbnails.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Different prediction options can be used in order to exploit the temporal and spatial similarities between the images.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Hence, file sizes can be drastically reduced when many images are stored in the same HEIF file.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] These data are not displayed as such, but used in various forms to complement another image item.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] and similar metadata which accompany the images stored in the HEIF file.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] As users cannot easily tell what encoding and encoding parameters an image was stored in, the HEIF container format can be confusing and makes comparison statements like “HEIF is better than JPEG” vague and inaccurate.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The Multi-Image Application Format (MIAF) is a restricted subset of HEIF specified as part of MPEG-A.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] It defines a set of additional constraints to simplify format options, specific alpha plane formats, profiles and levels as well as metadata formats and brands, and rules for how to extend the format.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC, ITU-T H.265) is an encoding format for graphic data, first standardized in 2013.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] It is the primarily used and implied default codec for HEIF as specified in the normative Annex B to ISO/IEC 23008-12 *HEVC Image File Format*.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] While not introduced formally in the standard, the initialism or acronym *HEIC* (High-Efficiency Image Codec) is used as a *brand* and in the MIME subtypes `image/heic` and `image/heic-sequence`.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] If the content conforms to certain HEVC profiles, more specific brands can be used: *HEIX* for Main 10 of HEVC, *HEIM* for (Multiview) Main profile, and *HEIS* for (Scalable) Main (10) profile of L-HEVC.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] A HEIC photo takes up about half the space of an equivalent-quality JPEG file.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The initial HEIF specification already defined the means of storing HEVC-encoded intra images (*i-frames*) and HEVC-encoded image sequences in which inter prediction is applied in a constrained manner.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] HEVC image players are required to support rectangular cropping and rotation by one, two, and three quarter-turns.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The primary use case for the mandatory support for rotation by 90 degrees is for images where the camera orientation is incorrectly detected or inferred.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The rotation requirement makes it possible to manually adjust the orientation of a still image or an image sequence without needing to re-encode it.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Cropping enables the image to be re-framed without re-encoding.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The HEVC file format also includes the option to store pre-derived images.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Samples in image sequence tracks must be either intra-coded images or inter-picture predicted images with reference to only intra-coded images.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] These constraints of inter-picture prediction reduce the decoding latency for accessing any particular image within a HEVC image sequence track.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The *.heic* and *.heics* file name extensions are conventionally used for HEVC-coded HEIF files.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Apple products, for instance, will only produce files with these extensions, which indicate clearly that the data went through HEVC encoding.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Advanced Video Coding (AVC, ITU-T H.264) is an older encoding format for video and images, first standardized in 2003.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] It is also specified as a codec to be supported in HEIF in normative Annex 5 to ISO/IEC 23008-12.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The registered MIME types are `image/avci` for still images and `image/avcs` for sequences.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Apple products support playback of AVC-encoded *.avci* still image files and *.avcs* image sequence files but will only generate *.heic* files.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] AV1 is a video encoding format that is intended to be royalty-free, developed by the Alliance for Open Media (AOMedia).
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] AV1 Image File Format (AVIF) is an image format based on this codec.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The registered MIME type is `image/avif` for both still images and image sequences, and *.avif* is the file name extension.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The original JPEG standard is the most commonly used and widely supported lossy image coding format.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] It was first released in 1992 by ITU-T and ISO/IEC.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Although Annex H to ISO/IEC 23008-12 specifies JPEG (and indirectly Motion JPEG) as a possible format for HEIF coded image data, it is used in HEIF only for thumbnails and other secondary images.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Therefore, neither a dedicated MIME subtype nor a special file extension is available for storage of JPEG files in HEIF container files.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] In 2017, Apple announced that it would adopt HEIC as the default image format in its new operating systems, gradually replacing JPEG.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The proprietary image format WXAM (or wxHEPC) developed by Tencent (used within, e.g., WeChat) is apparently based upon HEVC, as is SharpP, which was developed by their SNG (Social Network Group) division.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] However, their container format may not be HEIF-compatible.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] In March 2017, SharpP switched to AVS2 and was renamed TPG (*Tiny Portable Graphics*).
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] As of November 2025, only Safari supports HEIC format natively.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Edge, Chrome, Firefox, Opera, and Safari support AVIF.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] HEIF itself is a container that may not be subject to additional royalty fees for commercial ISOBMFF licensees.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Nokia also grants its patents on a royalty-free basis for non-commercial purposes.
[src:avif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] When containing images and image sequences encoded in a particular format (e.g., HEVC or AVC) its use becomes subject to the licensing of patents on the coding format.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] An **image file format** is a file format for a digital image.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] There are many formats that can be used, such as JPEG, PNG, and GIF.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Most formats up until 2022 were for storing 2D images, not 3D ones.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The data stored in an image file format may be compressed or uncompressed.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] If the data is compressed, it may be done so using lossy compression or lossless compression.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] For graphic design applications, vector formats are often used.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Some image file formats support transparency.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] A 3D image can be represented within a 2D format, as in a stereogram or autostereogram, but this 3D image will not be a true light field, and thereby may cause the vergence–accommodation conflict.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Image files are composed of digital data in one of these formats so that the data can be displayed on a digital (computer) display or printed out using a printer.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] A common method for displaying digital image information has historically been rasterization.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The size of raster image files is positively correlated with the number of pixels in the image and the color depth (bits per pixel).
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Images can be compressed in various ways, however.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] A compression algorithm stores either an exact representation or an approximation of the original image in a smaller number of bytes that can be expanded back to its uncompressed form with a corresponding decompression algorithm.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Images with the same number of pixels and color depth can have very different compressed file sizes.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Considering exactly the same compression, number of pixels, and color depth for two images, different graphical complexity of the original images may also result in very different file sizes after compression due to the nature of compression algorithms.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] With some compression formats, images that are less complex may result in smaller compressed file sizes.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] This characteristic sometimes results in a smaller file size for some lossless formats than lossy formats.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] For example, graphically simple images (i.e., images with large continuous regions like line art or animation sequences) may be losslessly compressed into a GIF or PNG format and result in a smaller file size than a lossy JPEG format.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] With vector images, the file size increases only with the addition of more vectors.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] There are two types of image file compression algorithms: lossless and lossy.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Lossless compression algorithms reduce file size while preserving a perfect copy of the original uncompressed image.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Lossless compression generally, but not always, results in larger files than lossy compression.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Lossless compression should be used to avoid accumulating stages of re-compression when editing images.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Lossy compression algorithms preserve a representation of the original uncompressed image that may appear to be a perfect copy, but is not a perfect copy.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Often lossy compression is able to achieve smaller file sizes than lossless compression.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Most lossy compression algorithms allow for variable compression that trades image quality for file size.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Including proprietary types, there are hundreds of image file types.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The PNG, JPEG, and GIF formats are most often used to display images on the Internet.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Some of these graphic formats are listed and briefly described below, separated into the two main families of graphics: raster and vector.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Raster images are further divided into formats primarily aimed at (web) delivery (i.e., supporting relatively strong compression) versus formats primarily aimed at authoring or interchange (uncompressed or only relatively weak compression).
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] In addition to straight image formats, Metafile formats are portable formats that can include both raster and vector information.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Examples are application-independent formats such as WMF and EMF.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The metafile format is an intermediate format.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Most applications open metafiles and then save them in their own native format.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Page description language refers to formats used to describe the layout of a printed page containing text, objects, and images.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] JPEG (Joint Photographic Experts Group) is a lossy compression method; JPEG-compressed images are usually stored in the JFIF (JPEG File Interchange Format) or the Exif (Exchangeable Image File Format) file format.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The JPEG filename extension is JPG or JPEG.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Nearly every digital camera can save images in the JPEG format, which supports eight-bit grayscale images and 24-bit color images (eight bits each for red, green, and blue).
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] JPEG applies lossy compression to images, which can result in a significant reduction of the file size.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Applications can determine the degree of compression to apply, and the amount of compression affects the visual quality of the result.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] When not too great, the compression does not noticeably affect or detract from the image's quality, but JPEG files suffer generational degradation when repeatedly edited and saved.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The GIF (Graphics Interchange Format) is in normal use limited to an 8-bit palette, or 256 colors (while 24-bit color depth is technically possible).
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] GIF is most suitable for storing graphics with few colors, such as simple diagrams, shapes, logos, and cartoon-style images, as it uses LZW lossless compression, which is more effective when large areas have a single color and less effective for photographic or dithered images.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Due to GIF's simplicity and age, it achieved almost universal software support.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Due to its animation capabilities, it is still widely used to provide image animation effects, despite its low compression ratio compared to modern video formats.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The PNG (Portable Network Graphics) file format was created as a free, open-source alternative to GIF.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The PNG file format supports 8-bit (256 colors) paletted images (with optional transparency for all palette colors) and 24-bit truecolor (16 million colors) or 48-bit truecolor with and without an alpha channel – while GIF supports only 8-bit palettes with a single transparent color.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Compared to JPEG, PNG excels when the image has large, uniformly colored areas.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Even for photographs – where JPEG is often the choice for final distribution since its lossy compression typically yields smaller file sizes – PNG is still well-suited to storing images during the editing process because of its lossless compression.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] PNG provides a patent-free replacement for GIF (though GIF is itself now patent-free) and can also replace many common uses of TIFF.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Indexed-color, grayscale, and truecolor images are supported, plus an optional alpha channel.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The Adam7 interlacing allows an early preview, even when only a small percentage of the image data has been transmitted—useful in online viewing applications like web browsers.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] PNG can store gamma and chromaticity data, as well as ICC profiles, for accurate color matching on heterogeneous platforms.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Animated formats derived from PNG are MNG and APNG, which is backwards compatible with PNG and supported by most browsers.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] JPEG 2000 is a compression standard enabling both lossless and lossy storage.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The compression methods used are different from the ones in standard JFIF/JPEG; they improve quality and compression ratios, but also require more computational power to process.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] JPEG 2000 also adds features that are missing in JPEG.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] It is not nearly as common as JPEG but it is used currently in professional movie editing and distribution (some digital cinemas, for example, use JPEG 2000 for individual movie frames).
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] WebP is an open image format released in 2010 that uses both lossless and lossy compression.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] It was designed by Google to reduce image file size to speed up web page loading: its principal purpose is to supersede JPEG as the primary format for photographs on the web.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] WebP is based on VP8's intra-frame coding and uses a container based on RIFF.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] In 2011, Google added an "Extended File Format" allowing WebP support for animation, ICC profile, XMP and Exif metadata, and tiling.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The support for animation allowed for converting older animated GIFs to animated WebP.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The WebP container (i.e., RIFF container for WebP) allows feature support over and above the basic use case of WebP (i.e., a file containing a single image encoded as a VP8 key frame).
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Most typical raster formats cannot store HDR data (32 bit floating point values per pixel component), which is why some relatively old or complex formats are still predominant here, and worth mentioning separately.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Newer alternatives are showing up, though.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] RGBE is the format for HDR images originating from Radiance and also supported by Adobe Photoshop.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] JPEG-HDR is a file format from Dolby Labs similar to RGBE encoding, standardized as JPEG XT Part 2.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] JPEG XT Part 7 includes support for encoding floating point HDR images in the base 8-bit JPEG file using enhancement layers encoded with four profiles (A-D); Profile A is based on the RGBE format and Profile B on the XDepth format from Trellis Management.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The High Efficiency Image File Format (HEIF) is an image container format that was standardized by MPEG on the basis of the ISO base media file format.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] While HEIF can be used with any image compression format, the HEIF standard specifies the storage of HEVC intra-coded images and HEVC-coded image sequences taking advantage of inter-picture prediction.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] AVIF is an image container, that is used to store AV1 encoded images.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] It was created by Alliance for open media (AOMedia) and is completely open source and royalty-free.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] It supports encoding images in 8, 10 and 12-bit depth.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] JPEG XL is a royalty-free raster-graphics file format that supports both lossy and lossless compression.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] It supports reversible recompression of existing JPEG files, as well as high-precision HDR (up to 32-bit floating point values per pixel component).
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] It is designed to be usable for both delivery and authoring use cases.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The TIFF (Tag Image File Format) format is a flexible format usually using either the TIFF or TIF filename extension.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The tag structure was designed to be easily extendible, and many vendors have introduced proprietary special-purpose tags – with the result that no one reader handles every flavor of TIFF file.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] TIFFs can be lossy or lossless, depending on the technique chosen for storing the pixel data.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Some offer relatively good lossless compression for bi-level (black&white) images.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Some digital cameras can save images in TIFF format, using the LZW compression algorithm for lossless storage.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] TIFF image format is not widely supported by web browsers, but it remains widely accepted as a photograph file standard in the printing business.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] TIFF can handle device-specific color spaces, such as the CMYK defined by a particular set of printing press inks.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] OCR (Optical Character Recognition) software packages commonly generate some form of TIFF image (often monochromatic) for scanned text pages.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The BMP file format (Windows bitmap) is a raster-based, device-independent file type designed in the early days of computer graphics.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] It handles graphic files within the Microsoft Windows OS.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Typically, BMP files are uncompressed and therefore large and lossless; their advantage is their simple structure and wide acceptance in Windows programs.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Netpbm format is a family including the portable pixmap file format (PPM), the portable graymap file format (PGM), and the portable bitmap file format (PBM).
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] These are either pure ASCII files or raw binary files with an ASCII header that provide very basic functionality and serve as a lowest common denominator for converting pixmap, graymap, or bitmap files between different platforms.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Several applications refer to them collectively as PNM (Portable Any Map).
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] As opposed to the raster image formats above (where the data describes the characteristics of each individual pixel), vector image formats contain a geometric description which can be rendered smoothly at any desired display size.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] At some point, all vector graphics must be rasterized in order to be displayed on digital monitors.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Vector images may also be displayed with analog CRT technology such as that used in some electronic test equipment, medical monitors, radar displays, laser shows and early video games.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Plotters are printers that use vector data rather than pixel data to draw graphics.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] CGM (Computer Graphics Metafile) is a file format for 2D vector graphics, raster graphics, and text, and is defined by ISO/IEC 8632.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] All graphical elements can be specified in a textual source file that can be compiled into a binary file or one of two text representations.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] CGM provides a means of graphics data interchange for computer representation of 2D graphical information independent from any particular application, system, platform, or device.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] It has been adopted to some extent in the areas of technical illustration and professional design, but has largely been superseded by formats such as SVG and DXF.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The Gerber format (aka Extended Gerber, RS-274X) is a 2D bi-level image description format developed by Ucamco.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] It is the de facto standard format for printed circuit board or PCB software.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] SVG (Scalable Vector Graphics) is an open standard created and developed by the World Wide Web Consortium to address the need (and attempts of several corporations) for a versatile, scriptable and all-purpose vector format for the web and otherwise.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] The SVG format does not have a compression scheme of its own, but due to the textual nature of XML, an SVG graphic can be compressed using a program such as gzip.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] Because of its scripting potential, SVG is a key component in web applications: interactive web pages that look and act like applications.
[src:avif-format/image-file-format] These are formats containing both pixel and vector data, possible other data, e.g. the interactive features of PDF.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] In information technology, **lossy compression**, or **irreversible compression**, is the class of data compression methods that uses inexact approximations and partial data discarding to represent the content.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] These techniques are used to reduce data size for storing, handling, and transmitting content.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Higher degrees of approximation create coarser images as more details are removed.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] This is opposed to lossless data compression (reversible data compression) which does not degrade the data.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] The amount of data reduction possible using lossy compression is much higher than using lossless techniques.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Well-designed lossy compression technology often reduces file sizes significantly before degradation is noticed by the end-user.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Even when noticeable by the user, further data reduction may be desirable (e.g., for real-time communication or to reduce transmission times or storage needs).
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] The most widely used lossy compression algorithm is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), first published by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Lossy compression is most commonly used to compress multimedia data (audio, video, and images), especially in applications such as streaming media and internet telephony.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] By contrast, lossless compression is typically required for text and data files, such as bank records and text articles.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] It can be advantageous to make a master lossless file which can then be used to produce additional copies from.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] This allows one to avoid basing new compressed copies on a lossy source file, which would yield additional artifacts and further unnecessary information loss.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] It is possible to compress many types of digital data in a way that reduces the size of a computer file needed to store it, or the bandwidth needed to transmit it, with no loss of the full information contained in the original file.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] A picture, for example, is converted to a digital file by considering it to be an array of dots and specifying the color and brightness of each dot.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] The original data contains a certain amount of information, and there is a lower bound to the size of a file that can still carry all the information.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Basic information theory says that there is an absolute limit in reducing the size of this data.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] When data is compressed, its entropy increases, and it cannot increase indefinitely.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] For example, a compressed ZIP file is smaller than its original, but repeatedly compressing the same file will not reduce the size to nothing.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Most compression algorithms can recognize when further compression would be pointless and would in fact increase the size of the data.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] In many cases, files or data streams contain more information than is needed.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] For example, a picture may have more detail than the eye can distinguish when reproduced at the largest size intended; likewise, an audio file does not need a lot of fine detail during a very loud passage.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Developing lossy compression techniques as closely matched to human perception as possible is a complex task.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Sometimes the ideal is a file that provides exactly the same perception as the original, with as much digital information as possible removed; other times, perceptible loss of quality is considered a valid tradeoff.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] The terms "irreversible" and "reversible" are preferred over "lossy" and "lossless" respectively for some applications, such as medical image compression, to circumvent the negative implications of "loss".
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] The type and amount of loss can affect the utility of the images.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Artifacts or undesirable effects of compression may be clearly discernible yet the result still useful for the intended purpose.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Or lossy compressed images may be 'visually lossless', or in the case of medical images, so-called diagnostically acceptable irreversible compression (DAIC) may have been applied.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Some forms of lossy compression can be thought of as an application of transform coding, which is a type of data compression used for digital images, digital audio signals, and digital video.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] The transformation is typically used to enable better (more targeted) quantization.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Knowledge of the application is used to choose information to discard, thereby lowering its bandwidth.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] The remaining information can then be compressed via a variety of methods.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] When the output is decoded, the result may not be identical to the original input, but is expected to be close enough for the purpose of the application.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] The most common form of lossy compression is a transform coding method, the discrete cosine transform (DCT), which was first published by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] DCT is the most widely used form of lossy compression, for popular image compression formats (such as JPEG), video coding standards (such as MPEG and H.264/AVC) and audio compression formats (such as MP3 and AAC).
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] In the case of audio data, a popular form of transform coding is perceptual coding, which transforms the raw data to a domain that more accurately reflects the information content.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] For example, rather than expressing a sound file as the amplitude levels over time, one may express it as the frequency spectrum over time, which corresponds more accurately to human audio perception.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] This is because uncompressed audio can only reduce file size by lowering bit rate or depth, whereas compressing audio can reduce size while maintaining bit rate and depth.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] This compression becomes a selective loss of the least significant data, rather than losing data across the board.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Further, a transform coding may provide a better domain for manipulating or otherwise editing the data – for example, equalization of audio is most naturally expressed in the frequency domain (boost the bass, for instance) rather than in the raw time domain.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] From this point of view, perceptual encoding is not essentially about *discarding* data, but rather about a *better representation* of data.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Another use is for backward compatibility and graceful degradation: in color television, encoding color via a luminance-chrominance transform domain (such as YUV) means that black-and-white sets display the luminance, while ignoring the color information.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Lossy compression formats suffer from generation loss: repeatedly compressing and decompressing the file will cause it to progressively lose quality.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] This is in contrast with lossless data compression, where data will not be lost via the use of such a procedure.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Information-theoretical foundations for lossy data compression are provided by rate-distortion theory.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Much like the use of probability in optimal coding theory, rate-distortion theory heavily draws on Bayesian estimation and decision theory in order to model perceptual distortion and even aesthetic judgment.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] In some systems the two techniques are combined, with transform codecs being used to compress the error signals generated by the predictive stage.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] The advantage of lossy methods over lossless methods is that in some cases a lossy method can produce a much smaller compressed file than any lossless method, while still meeting the requirements of the application.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Lossy methods are most often used for compressing sound, images or videos.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] This is because these types of data are intended for human interpretation where the mind can easily "fill in the blanks" or see past very minor errors or inconsistencies – ideally lossy compression is transparent (imperceptible), which can be verified via an ABX test.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Data files using lossy compression are smaller in size and thus cost less to store and to transmit over the Internet, a crucial consideration for streaming video services such as Netflix and streaming audio services such as Spotify.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] When a user acquires a lossily compressed file, (for example, to reduce download time) the retrieved file can be quite different from the original at the bit level while being indistinguishable to the human ear or eye for most practical purposes.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Many compression methods focus on the idiosyncrasies of human physiology, taking into account, for instance, that the human eye can see only certain wavelengths of light.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] The psychoacoustic model describes how sound can be highly compressed without degrading perceived quality.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Flaws caused by lossy compression that are noticeable to the human eye or ear are known as compression artifacts.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] The compression ratio (that is, the size of the compressed file compared to that of the uncompressed file) of lossy video codecs is nearly always far superior to that of the audio and still-image equivalents.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] An important caveat about lossy compression (formally transcoding), is that editing lossily compressed files causes digital generation loss from the re-encoding.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] This can be avoided by only producing lossy files from (lossless) originals and only editing (copies of) original files, such as images in raw image format instead of JPEG.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] If data which has been compressed lossily is decoded and compressed losslessly, the size of the result can be comparable with the size of the data before lossy compression, but the data already lost cannot be recovered.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] When deciding to use lossy conversion without keeping the original, format conversion may be needed in the future to achieve compatibility with software or devices (format shifting), or to avoid paying patent royalties for decoding or distribution of compressed files.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] By modifying the compressed data directly without decoding and re-encoding, some editing of lossily compressed files without degradation of quality is possible.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Editing which reduces the file size as if it had been compressed to a greater degree, but without more loss than this, is sometimes also possible.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] The primary programs for lossless editing of JPEGs are `jpegtran`, and the derived `exiftran` (which also preserves Exif information), and Jpegcrop (which provides a Windows interface).
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] These allow the image to be cropped, rotated, flipped, and flopped, or even converted to grayscale (by dropping the chrominance channel).
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] While unwanted information is destroyed, the quality of the remaining portion is unchanged.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Some other transforms are possible to some extent, such as joining images with the same encoding (composing side by side, as on a grid) or pasting images such as logos onto existing images (both via Jpegjoin), or scaling.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] The freeware Windows-only IrfanView has some lossless JPEG operations in its `JPG_TRANSFORM` plugin.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Metadata, such as ID3 tags, Vorbis comments, or Exif information, can usually be modified or removed without modifying the underlying data.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Some well-known designs that have this capability include JPEG 2000 for still images and H.264/MPEG-4 AVC based Scalable Video Coding for video.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Such schemes have also been standardized for older designs as well, such as JPEG images with progressive encoding, and MPEG-2 and MPEG-4 Part 2 video, although those prior schemes had limited success in terms of adoption into real-world common usage.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Similar techniques are used in mipmaps, pyramid representations, and more sophisticated scale space methods.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Some audio formats feature a combination of a lossy format and a lossless correction which when combined reproduce the original signal; the correction can be stripped, leaving a smaller, lossily compressed, file.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Such formats include MPEG-4 SLS (Scalable to Lossless), WavPack, OptimFROG DualStream, and DTS-HD Master Audio in lossless (XLL) mode).
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Researchers have performed lossy compression on text by either using a thesaurus to substitute short words for long ones, or generative text techniques, although these sometimes fall into the related category of lossy data conversion.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] A general kind of lossy compression is to lower the resolution of an image, as in image scaling, particularly decimation.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] One may also remove less "lower information" parts of an image, such as by seam carving.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Many media transforms, such as Gaussian blur, are, like lossy compression, irreversible: the original signal cannot be reconstructed from the transformed signal.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] However, in general these will have the same size as the original, and are not a form of compression.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Lowering resolution has practical uses, as the NASA New Horizons craft transmitted thumbnails of its encounter with Pluto-Charon before it sent the higher resolution images.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Another solution for slow connections is the usage of Image interlacing which progressively defines the image.
[src:avif-format/lossy-compression] Thus a partial transmission is enough to preview the final image, in a lower resolution version, without creating a scaled and a full version too.
